{
  "texts": [
    "What the agent does is what happens; and what happens is a pattern in events to which persons -self-and other-interpreting rational agents -are attuned in the ordinary practice of psychological explanation.",
    "In a world containing rational agents, a wide segment of the causal networks surrounding them enters into a teleological ordering present just when actions are done with intention; and, whatever else they are, the patterns that exemplify this order are things that constitutively depend on the events that make them up.",
    "In light of these claims, consider again the evidence canvased above (in §3.2) that much of what we pretheoretically think of as cognition is constituted by actions performed in and with an environment (this was P2 of the argument sketch given in §3.4).",
    "These actions, we have seen, recruit external resources in the form of artefacts, reliable environmental structure, patterns of feedback and 'social technologies' like writing systems.",
    "While bodily movements are a means to access such resources, their cognitive significance is only apparent when described in the wider context of what happens when agents do so."
  ]
}